name: The Morning Call
articlebody:
In a Lehigh County courtroom over the last two weeks, jurors have watched frame-by-frame video of Joseph Santos' being fatally shot and listened to experts analyze the actions of a former South Whitehall Township police officer charged in the killing.
Outside the courtroom, a crisis of unprecedented proportions has been unfolding, as state officials ordered schools and businesses shuttered, the stock market plunged day after day and cases of potentially deadly coronavirus spread exponentially across the state.
And after testimony in Jonathan Roselle's voluntary manslaughter trial concluded Wednesday, the state Supreme Court ordered all Pennsylvania courts to close their doors to the public until at least April 3. A day later, the jury found Roselle not guilty of voluntary manslaughter.
Holding a criminal trial under such conditions requires care, legal experts say, to ensure jurors are focused on the evidence being presented by both sides and not preoccupied by the upheaval in the world beyond the courthouse steps. The constitutional rights to a fair trial and justice for the defendant and victims hangs in the balance.
"I doubt that anyone, either prosecution or defense, wants a jury that is pressured to return a verdict just so that people can get home and be safe," said Jules Epstein, a law professor at Temple University who also handles appeals in death penalty cases.
"It makes it harder for jurors to pay attention when they are worried about their health or their lives," he said.
Such distraction could lead to an unfair outcome for either side, said jury consultant Carol Lieberman.
"If they feel like we've heard enough, they might discount the defense," Lieberman said. "Or it could go the other way, like, 'I want to go home. I do still have a doubt, so I can't convict him.'"
Lehigh County Judge Kelly Banach, who presided over the trial, said she and court officials were mindful of the effect the outside events could have on the jury. She was confident jurors were able to set them aside.
"I mention every day, 'I hope folks are well. We are taking all the steps to keep people comfortable. If anybody feels that they are not comfortable, please let us know, we'll do our best,'" Banach said in an interview Wednesday.
No one, Banach said, expressed unease about being in her courtroom, which was reduced in capacity to allow people to sit farther apart. But on Wednesday, one of her staffers, the court crier who makes public announcements, excused himself from the case after listening to the pleas from his family, she said.
"The person who feels least comfortable is me," Banach said. "Because I feel responsible for everybody."
Checking in with jurors and lawyers to ensure there are no problems is an important safeguard for the integrity of a trial, Epstein said.
"If someone finds out later that the jurors were freaking out, and no one asked and the trial went on, that could lead to appeal after appeal after appeal," he said.
Roselle is charged in the July 2018 shooting of Santos, 44, of Hasbrouck Heights, New Jersey. Santos, who was unarmed, had been at Dorney Park and Wildwater Kingdom for a family gathering before leaving the park by himself in the early evening. Jurors started deliberating Thursday afternoon.
Roselle was responding to reports of Santos holding up traffic on Hamilton Boulevard, breaking one car window and banging on others. Jurors also heard audio from Roselle's body camera in which he tells a fellow officer Santos, "just kept coming at me. I didn't know what to do."
The shooting sparked protests by civil rights and Latino community groups, who labeled the shooting an example of systemic injustice, of law enforcement victimizing people of color. As Roselle's trial approached, court officials prepared for a new round of protests and took steps to ensure they would not interfere or taint jurors, Banach said.
The court devised an intricate security plan involving the sheriff's department, the defense and the district attorney's office in case anyone attempted to be disruptive.
Jurors were directed to a special parking area, where sheriff's deputies met and escorted them to a nonpublic entrance of the Lehigh County Courthouse. They took a private elevator to the fourth floor.
"It turned out the security plans we had in place, if you will, became almost like a health security plan," Banach said, adding that they didn't come into contact with anyone but the people involved in the trial.
In addition to being kept apart from the public, the 12 jurors and four alternates were divided between two deliberation rooms when the trial was in recess to comply with the federal government guideline to avoid gatherings of more than 10 people. In the courtroom, however, the jury sat in the jury box about 2 feet apart. They jury used an adjacent courtroom instead of a smaller deliberation room to reach a verdict.
Had the trial been called off because of the national crisis, that would not have been unprecedented.
Former Northampton County District Attorney John Morganelli was delivering an opening statement in a murder trial when the Sept. 11, 2001, attacks on the World Trade Center and Pentagon happened.
The trial was halted for the day, and when jurors returned on Sept. 12, Judge Jack Panella declared a mistrial for Brandon Bloss and Michelle Hetzel, citing fears that people were preoccupied with the attacks, and because some witnesses became unavailable.
In response to a letter Wednesday from Pennsylvania Health Secretary Dr. Rachel Levine urging the courts to shut down, state Supreme Court Chief Justice Thomas Saylor ordered them closed to the public for nonessential functions.
The order also encourages courts to use technology to conduct court proceedings. While Pennsylvania courts do not allow members of the public or journalists to bring cameras into courtrooms, they use video conferencing equipment in many civil matters, but its use in criminal cases is limited. Courts in Lehigh and Northampton counties routinely use video to conduct first appearances and bail hearings.
Tele-presence technology has advanced to the point where it can be used for certain aspects of the court system, said Mehran Ebadolahi, who founded a company called TestMax to provide one-on-one instruction to prospective law students and those studying for bar exams. With coronavirus shutting down courthouses, proceedings such as depositions, jury selection and even civil trials could be carried out with jurors and witnesses participating remotely, Ebadolahi said.
Criminal trials, with more rigid constitutional protections such as the right to confront one's accuser, would be more difficult to do remotely, he conceded.
Banach said she expected the biggest issue in jury selection to be whether anyone had heard about the case, but by the time she and the lawyers started interviewing potential jurors, coronavirus had become a topic.
"In my mind we were going to have a bunch of people coming in saying, 'I'm afraid of the virus, I don't want to get sick, you know I live with an older person, I have to check on my mom, I have small kids, whatever it was,'" she said.
She braced for the possibility that if they could not pick a jury in two days, the trial might be postponed until the crisis had abated.
"What I found was, as we talked to every juror, not one person raised it, not one prospective juror raised the issue," Banach said.
The court encountered no issues with jurors having conversations about coronavirus and Banach called the group unlike any she has encountered in 17 years as a judge.
"I think they are invested, they understand how important it is for the defendant and the victim's family to bring this to a close. They are just an incredible group of people," she said.
Morning Call reporters Michelle Merlin and Laurie Mason Schroeder contributed to this report.
headline: Coronavirus doesn't distract Roselle jury, which heard case of officer involved shooting during crisis
